2 Whether au innocent citizen may be delivered into the hands

³* This is an example of the evil of laying down rules for cases of necessity. If a city under the terror of destruction from a cruel enemy, should give up an inno- cent person to death, we might excuse them when the thing was done3 but we can hardly look upon it as a speculative opinion which they may morally hold beforehand, that men are right in doing so. The certainty of saving themselves by such means must be doubtful, as Barbeyrac says: and no protest could be strong enough to express the horror which the Rulers of a State ought to feel towards such a step.
